  <li id="comment-12198" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/12089397499074523719" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Minti</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2008/12/for-that-very-reason/#comment-12198"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2009-04-02T20:13:00-04:00">Thursday, April 2, 2009 at 8:13 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I made these yesterday with half the recipe. Still warm from the oven, they were lightly crisp on the outside but melt in your mouth. </></>I&#8217;ll try warming them in the microwave the next time to see if that works.</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-44560" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Joanne Owens</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2008/12/for-that-very-reason/#comment-44560"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2015-12-20T11:37:39-05:00">Sunday, December 20, 2015 at 11:37 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I made this recipe. While they were delicious, they were too dry and crumbly to serve at my party.  At first I thought it was because I used Land O Lakes instead of Lurpak, but after studying a great article comparing butters and their baking results (<a href="http://www.sfgate.com/recipes/article/When-Put-to-the-Test-Here-s-How-Butter-Brands-3236719.php" rel="nofollow ugc">http://www.sfgate.com/recipes/article/When-Put-to-the-Test-Here-s-How-Butter-Brands-3236719.php</a>) I know if anything the Lurpak would have made them flakier/dryer. So the problem was with my measurement of the flour. Without using a scale, it&#8217;s easy to put too much flour into the measuring cup.  I will try these again because they&#8217;re the taste I want, but if anyone can share their secrets for getting an accurate measure, I&#8217;d welcome it.  Also, if I do buy a scale, how do I know what the weight should be if the recipe doesn&#8217;t specify?</p>
    </div>

      <ol class="children">
  <li id="comment-44622" class="comment byuser comment-author-molly bypostauthor odd alt depth-2">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://orangette.com" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Molly</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2008/12/for-that-very-reason/#comment-44622"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2015-12-24T23:16:03-05:00">Thursday, December 24, 2015 at 11:16 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Joanne, I&#8217;m sorry they were crumbly!  That&#8217;s frustrating.  I started adding weight measurements to my recipes in 2011, but sadly, I wasn&#8217;t doing them at the time I posted this recipe.  That said, in general, 1 cup of all-purpose flour weighs between 125 and 140 grams.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
          </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ol><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-44634" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Joanne Owens</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2008/12/for-that-very-reason/#comment-44634"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2015-12-25T08:41:03-05:00">Friday, December 25, 2015 at 8:41 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I loved the taste so much I made them twice more this week to figure out how to conquer the crumble. I&#8217;m now careful to spoon the flour gently into the measuring cup and then level. I also add 1T vanilla when I add the sugar. I&#8217;ve tried freezing them, but the family had started eating them straight from the freezer! Just can&#8217;t keep them in the house.</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-44635" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Joanne Owens</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2008/12/for-that-very-reason/#comment-44635"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2015-12-25T08:47:41-05:00">Friday, December 25, 2015 at 8:47 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I should also mention that I enjoy a thicker cookie, so I rolled my dough to 3/4 inch. To keep the dough from being overworked, instead of rerolling  multiple times I roll the scaps into balls and press with my hand or bottom of a cup to make a round cookie. My final note after all my trials. Be sure to remove cookies when a you see a little brown on the edges but they&#8217;re still quite light. Any browning on the bottom changes the taste of the cookie</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-53210" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Joanne Owens</cite></div>
